explanationMd:
### How React detects state changes
React uses `Object.is()` to compare the previous and next state value. For objects, `Object.is(a, b)` is `true` only when `a` and `b` are the **same object in memory** (same reference).

```js
const a = { role: 'viewer' };
a.role = 'admin';  // mutate
Object.is(a, a)    // true — still the same object reference
```

When you call `setUser(user)` after mutating `user`, React sees the same reference and bails out.

### The fix: always return new objects from state updates
```js
// Wrong — mutates, same reference:
user.role = 'admin';
setUser(user);

// Correct — new object, different reference:
setUser({ ...user, role: 'admin' });
```

### Updating nested state
```js
// Nested mutation — bug:
state.user.address.city = 'London';
setState(state);

// Correct — new objects at every level that changed:
setState({
  ...state,
  user: { ...state.user, address: { ...state.user.address, city: 'London' } }
});
```

tutorial.bodyMd:
## React State Immutability: Why You Must Create New Objects

### How React decides to re-render
When you call a state setter (like `setUser`), React compares the previous state with the new value using `Object.is()`. For primitive values, this is a value comparison:

```js
Object.is(1, 1)           // true  — same value
Object.is('hello', 'hi') // false — different values
```

For objects, `Object.is()` compares **references** — whether the two variables point to the exact same object in memory:

```js
const a = { role: 'viewer' };
const b = { role: 'viewer' };
Object.is(a, a)   // true  — same reference
Object.is(a, b)   // false — different references (even though contents match)
```

### What happens when you mutate
When you write `user.role = 'admin'` and then call `setUser(user)`, you are passing the **same object reference**. React compares it to the previous state, sees the same reference, and concludes nothing changed — skipping the re-render entirely.

The property was changed in memory, but React never knows.

### The rule: treat state as read-only
Never modify state values directly. Always create a new value:

```js
// Don't mutate:
user.role = 'admin';

// Do create new:
const updatedUser = { ...user, role: 'admin' };
setUser(updatedUser);

// Or inline:
setUser({ ...user, role: 'admin' });
```

### The spread operator for state updates
The object spread `{ ...existing, key: newValue }` copies all properties from `existing` into a new object, then overwrites `key`:

```js
const user = { name: 'Alice', role: 'viewer', active: true };

// Update only the role:
const updated = { ...user, role: 'admin' };
// { name: 'Alice', role: 'admin', active: true }
```

This pattern works for any depth of update to the root level.

### Updating arrays in state
The same principle applies to arrays — never mutate, always create new:

```js
const [items, setItems] = useState(['a', 'b', 'c']);

// Wrong — mutation:
items.push('d');
setItems(items);   // same reference, no re-render

// Correct — new array:
setItems([...items, 'd']);

// Removing an item:
setItems(items.filter(item => item !== 'b'));

// Updating one item:
setItems(items.map(item => item === 'b' ? 'B' : item));
```

### Functional updates for derived state
When the new state depends on the previous state, use the functional form:

```js
setCount(prevCount => prevCount + 1);           // safe
setUser(prevUser => ({ ...prevUser, role: 'admin' }));  // safe
```

This matters in React 18+ where multiple `setState` calls can be batched — the functional form always receives the latest state.

### Libraries that help: Immer
For deeply nested state, the spread syntax becomes verbose. **Immer** lets you write mutation-style code that secretly produces new objects:

```js
import { produce } from 'immer';

setState(produce(draft => {
  draft.user.address.city = 'London';  // looks like mutation
  // Immer creates new objects at every changed level
}));
```

### You just learned
React compares state by reference. Mutating a state object and calling `setState(sameObj)` does not trigger a re-render because the reference hasn't changed. Always create new objects: `setState({ ...prev, key: newValue })` for objects, and `[...arr, item]` / `arr.filter()` / `arr.map()` for arrays.
